{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hawthorne_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205698255/1937123001/0399.xml":{"full_text":"WASHINGTON FORECAST\nMostly cloudy tonight and Friday; not\nmuch change in temperature; lowest tem\nperature tonight about 36. (See Page 4.)\nNo. 17,614\nIncome and Sales Taxes Proposed for District\nKNUDSEN DUE\nTO TESTIFY\nON RECESSION\nG. M. Head to Talk\nTo Senate Jan. 6\nDETROIT, Dec. 30 (1.N.5.).\nWilliam S. Knudsen, General Mo\ntors Corporation president, today\nannounced that he would testify\nfit a U. S. Senate hearing next\nThursday to give his views on the\ncauses of the business recession.\nThe General Motors Corporation\nearlier this week announced layoff\nof 30,000 men and placed its 205,-\n000 other workers in the United\nStates on a 24-hour week.\nWIRES EXCHANGED\nKnudsen\u2019s plan was made known\nIn an exchange of telegrams with\nSenator James F. Byrnes (D.),\nchairman of the committee in the\nSenate assigned to probe the busi\nness collapse.\nSenator Byrnes\u2019 telegram in part\nto Knudsen follows:\n\u201cMy committee considers it\nexceedingly important to hear\nfrom you at the opening of our\nInvestigation next week, particu\nlarly in view of reported unem\nployment in the automobile in\ndustry.\n\u201cWill you not kindly make\nyour \u00abmngements to appear be\nfore the committee forenoon,\nThursday, January 6, to give the\ncommittee the latest informa\ntion regarding production and\nemployment prospects in your\nindustry.\u2019\u2019\nTo which Knudsen replied by\nwire:\n\u201cI will make arrangements to\nrearrange my business trip in\nthe field to permit me to accept\nyour invitation to appear on\nJanuary 6.\u2019\u2019\nSPEEDED BY LAYOFF\nMeanwhile, it was learned that\nthe GM president had been asked\nonce before by committee mem\nbers to testify. He had tentatively\nagreed to appear at Washington\non January 28. However, the GM\nannouncement concerning layoffs\nwas believed to have led the Sen\nate investigators to request Knud\neen to appear at the earlier date.\nAlfred E. Smith, 64,\nBans Birthday Fuss\nNEW YORK, Dec. 30 (1.N.5.).\nAlfred E. Smith, 64 years old to\nday, planned to observe the an\nniversary quietly. Refusing to\nallow any fuss over the event, the\nformer Governor announced he\nwould spend the day just the\nsame as any other day.\nSlump Hits CIO Auto Union;\nOrganizers Face Layoff\nDETROIT, Dec. 30 (1.N.5.). \u2014The business recession hit\nthe ClO\u2019s United Automobile Workers Union today.\ni\nHOMER MARTIN\n{>ay roll. Martin was unable to say how many would be\ngid off.\nEntered aa Second Claes Matter at\nbuet office at Washington. D. C.\nSlaying Mystery\nOn Yacht Deepens\nj\nI\ni\nInternational New* Sonndphote\nABOARD THIS trim yacht, the Aafje, being towed into\nLos Angeles by a Coast Guard cutter, is secreted a mystery\nof the sea. There are six living people aboard and one\ndead man, Dwight Faulding, rich hotel man, reported\nto have been slain.\nIBs i\nSM'a* I\nK\nDWIGHT L. FAULDING\nCOURT REFUSES\nTO ACCUSE FORD\nLANSING, Mich., Dec. 30\n(I.N.S.).\u2014The Michigan Supreme\nCourt, scrawling the one word\n\"denied\u201d across a small slip of\npaper, today brought an end to\npossible criminal prosecution of\nthe Ford Motor Company and\neight of its workers for an alleged\nattack on CIO unionists last May\n26.\nMOBS RIOT IN EGYPT\nPORT SAID, Dec. 30 (1.N.5.).\nNumerous bloody clashes between\npolice and mobs of Wafdi (nation\nalists) were reported today in the\ninterior of Egypt. Authorities ad\nmitted the situation \"serious,\u201d but\ncontended, in spite of riot reports,\nthat the country is \u201ccalm.\u201d\nHomer Martin, president\nof the UAW, mailed letters\nto. all organizers warning\n\u201cthe economic recession\u201d\nwill soon make it neces\nsary to lay off a consider\nable number of them.\nMartin said the layoffs\nwould be guided by senior\nity and not \u201cpersonal or\nfactional\u201d reasons. He also\npointed out the interna\ntional union must keep\nwithin its income and that\n\u201cdrastic\u201d cuts in personnel\nwere under consideration.\nA spokesman for the\nunion said about 175 or\nganizers are now on the\nTH Ve\u2018 T P 3 T A E L S OiftBIMES\nNEWSPAPER. JI X JI JK\u2014-7\nOne of Passengers Is\nUnidentified On\nSchooner\nLOS ANGELES, Dec. 30 (1.N.5.).\nWith the yacht Aafje being towed\nto Los Angeles harbor, the owner\nreported slain, mystery deepened\ntoday over the identity and where\nabouts of \"Jack Morgan,\u201d one of\nthe eight persons who sailed away\nwith the ship of strange drama\nwhen it disappeared December 20,\nlast.\nCoast Guard reports failed to\nlist Morgan as a passenger on\nthe ill-fated Aafje at the present\ntime. Yet, 48 hours ago, a Navy\nsea plane pilot, who brought his\nplane down alongside the help\nlessly drifting yacht, was reported\nto have radioed his base at San\nDiego that he had conversed with\na Jack Morgan aboard the yacht.\nREPORTS OWNER DEAD\nIt was the Navy pilot who first\nflashed word that Dwight L.\nFaulding, wealthy Santa Barbara,\nCal., hotel proprietor, and owner\nof the Aafje, was lying dead on\nthe foredeck of the mystery\nschooner yacht. The pilot, whose\nname was withheld by Navy\nauthorities at San Diego, was said\nto have repo\u2019ted \u201cthere is trouble\naboard\u2014Faulting has been shot.\u201d\nDiscovery of Faulding\u2019s violent\ndeath, reported in secrecy-veiled\ndispatches as murder, was coin\ncidental with the rescue of three\nwomen, one of them an expectant\nmother, two men and a boy, who\nhad been on the distressed vessel\nwithout food or water for three or\nmore days.\nTHOSE RESCUED\nThe rescued are:\nMrs. Gertrude Turner, and her\nson, Robert, 8, of Goleta, Cal.\nMrs. Jack Morgan, Los Angeles.\nMiss Elsie Berdan, Los Angeles.\nGeorge Spemak, Los Angeles.\nRobert Horne, Los Angeles.\nRescue of the passengers from\nthe stricken craft, who were trans\nferred to the patrol boat Perseus,\nwas made after secret report that\nFaulding had been slain.\nThe race to the Aafje began\nTuesday night with W. H. Os\nburne, a Department of Justice\nagent, following the Perseus in\nanother cutter.\nThe Department of Justice has\ntaken full charge of the investiga\ntion.\nIt was reported that Faulding\nhad been shot to death. G-men\nhave indicated they bad been\ngiven the name of a suspect.\nSTOCKS OPEN HIGHER\nNEW YORK, Det. 30 <LN.S.).\nInitial stock market dealings to\nday found the previous session\u2019s\nlate recovery being extended a\npoint or so through the general\nlist. Trading was at much slower\npace, however, and the tape was\ndotted with frequent cash sales\nin the usual year-end tax selling.\nTHURSDAY, DECEMBER 30, 1937\nJAPAN OFFERS!\nPEACE TERMS\nTO GEN. CHIANG\nConditions Severe,\nSays Moscow\nMore dramatic pictures\nof the sinking of the\nPanay will be found on\nPage 4.\nMOSCOW, Dec. 30 (1.N.5.).\nJapanese terms for peace with\nChina have been conveyed to\nGeneralissimo Chiang Kai-Shek\u2019s\nregime, Moscow newspapers stated\ntoday.\nThe papers published a six-point\nresume of the alleged peace terms,\nand said they had been communi\ncated to China by the German\nambassador there.\nTERMS OF PEACE\nAs reported in the Moscow\nnewspapers, the peace terms are\nas follows:\n1. An economic agreement to\nbe concluded at Japan\u2019s dicta\ntion.\n2. Renunciation of China\u2019s\nstruggle against Japan and con\nclusion of a Sino-Japanese anti-\nCommunist agreement.\n3. Establishment of perma\nnent Japanese military garri\nsons in important Chinese areas.\n\"4. Establishment of- demili\ntarized zones.\n5. Creation of independent\nInner Mongolian and North\nChina government.\n6. Payment of war indemni\nties by China.\nMEDIATION TRIED\nLONDON, Dec. 30 (IJT.S.).\u2014\nCertain powers again are actively\nattempting to mediate the Sino-\nJapanese conflict, according to re\nliable quarters at Hankow, a Reu\nter dispatch from the temporary\nChinese capital reported today.\nThe dispatch said the Chinese\nare maintaining complete silence,\napparently owing to the failure of\nprevious peace efforts and small\nlikelihood the renewed attempts\nwill prove successful.\n(Other news of Chinese crisis on\nPage 2)\nFall of Gibraltar\nTo Italy Foreseen\nANN ARBOR, Mich., Dec. 30\n(I.N.S.).\u2014The Rock of Gibraltar\nis vulnerable, according to Prof.\nDerwent Whittlesley of Harvard\nUniversity today.\nDr. Whittesley told the Michi\ngan convention of geographers\nWednesday that Italy\u2019s interven\ntion in the Spanish civil war may\nendanger Great Britain\u2019s Gibral\ntar stronghold. He added strong\nSpanish positions and modem de\nvelopment of artillery have made\nthe rock vulnerable.\nFreighter in Mud;\nTugs Standing By\nDETROIT, Dec. 30 (I.NJS.).\nTugs were to attempt to free the\nfreighter John Watt from a mud\nbank in the Detroit River four\nmiles below Bob-Lo Island today\nafter the ship ran aground during\na fog Wednesday.\nThe vessel, one of the largest\non the lakes and carrying a crew\nof 35, was in no danger. It had\nbeen en route from Toledo to De\ntroit with a cargo of coal.\nThroat Blocked,\nMd. Baby Dies\nBaby Lois Deal, of Mitchellville,\nMd., died early today in Children\u2019s\nHospital. Physicians said the\nyear-old infant had a foreign sub\nstance lodged in her throat. She\nwas brought to the hospital last\nmidnight by her parents.\ni|Guards, Police Move to Halt\n\u2018Rebellion\u2019 Strikes in Paris\nMS (fc\nx Jr Jr si y\n111 1 I jflE j I\nCHEERING AND singing, a group of\nworkers in a foodstuff warehouse are\nshown as they staged a strike iji P#ris on\nMARKETCLOSED\nIN RUMANIA\nBUCHAREST, Rumania, Dec.\n30 (I.N.S.).\u2014Octavian Goga, Ru\nmania\u2019s new premier, took swift\nand drastic measures today to halt\nfinancial opposition to his freshly\ninaugurated regime.\nThe government issued a decree\nclosing the Bucharest stock ex\nchange and strictly forbidding all\nfinancial transactions until Jan\nuary 10.\nThis action was taken after the\nstock market and other financial\nquarters had exhibited marked\nnervousness as a result of Goga\u2019s\nchoice for the Premiership.\nAt the same time, in another\nmove seen as bringing Rumania\ncloser to a semi-fascist dictator\nship, Goga, leader of the anti\nsemitic Christian Socialist Party,\nsuppressed three Liberal demo\ncratic newspapers.\nThis was interpreted in diplo\nmatic circles as a move toward a\nvirtually totalitarian regime.\nForeign observers believed this\ntrend would lead Rumania closer\nto Nazi Germany and Fascist Italy\nand further away from France\nand the little entente.\nAt the same time, there were ru\nmors the new cabinet might make\nsome move to restrict or even abol\nish the powers of the Rumanian\nparliament.\nDalhover\u2019s $2,650\nSued for as Loot\nSOUTH BEND, Ind., Dec. 30\n(IJf.S.).\u2014The Maryland Casualty\nCompany today has a suit on file\nto obtain $2,650 found on James\nDalhover, Brady mobster, when\nhe was captured in Bangor, Me.,\non October 12. The company paid\n$7,250 in insurance to the People\u2019s\nExchange Bank of Thorpe, Wis\u201e\nafter a hold-up there on August\n29, and claims the money found\non Dalhover was part of the loot\ntaken in that robbery.\n25 KILLED IN QUAKE\nBUENOS AIRES, Dec. 30\n(I.N.S.).\u2014At least 25 persons were\nkilled and 150 Injured in an earth\nquake that rocked the Htiachon\nand Oxapampa regions of Peru.\nDecember 22, the beginning of the threats\nof a general walkout of all labor in the\nFrench capital. The strike ended today.\nWorkers Are on Jobs\nWith Promise\nO f Pay Rise\nPARIS, Dec. 30 -(l.N.S.).\u2014Vet\neran mobile guards and police\ntook stern action today to end\nstrikes by rebellious workers\nwhich continued in spite of gov\nernment orders.\nTroops manned military trucks\nto deliver newspapers and bring\nproduce into Paris as private\ntransport workers refused to re\nsume work.\nSoldiers armed with rifles and\npolice sped to suburban Nanterre,\nwhere employes in an important\ngas plant suddenly called a sit\ndown strike in defiance of orders\nfrom the labor federation. The\ntroops were ordered to eject the\nstrikers forcibly, if necessary.\nAfter staging a one-day strike\nthat brought government threats\nof armed force to break it, Paris\u2019\npublic utilities workers returned\nto their jobs today after reaching\na compromise agreement for in\ncreased pay.\nOfficials said exact terms of the\nagreement which ended the strike\nhave not yet been ironed out, but\nthat the Paris municipal council\nis meeting this afternoon to dis-\ncuss this matter.\nAs a result, in contrast to the\ntraffic chaos that prevailed yester\nday, there were only slight delays\nin subway service this morning as\nthe city\u2019s hordes of office workers\nand others rushed to their places\nof employment.\nTREASURY CONDITION\nGN.S.) Treasury balance De\ncember 28: $2,988,707,804.48; in\nternal revenue. $3,655,621.21; cus\ntoms receipts, $26,258,970.93.\nRescue Squad Loses Fight\nTo Save Gas Victim\u2019s Life\nMembers of the Fire Rescue\nSquad battled for an hour\nagainst death today in an apart\nment at 2630 Adams Mill Rd.\nN. W. \u2014and lost.\nThe squad was summoned after\nClayton A. Brown, 37, a salesman,\nwas found unconscious in the\nkitchen of his apartment\u2014his\nhead in the stove oven and all\nthe gas jets turned on.\nWith pulmotor and artificial\nHOME\nE DITION\nEXTEND SILVER\nBUYING PACTS\n(1.N.5.). The United States\nhas agreed to continue its silver\nbuying agreement with Canada\nand China, Secretary of the\nTreasury Morgenthau announced\ntoday.\nUnder an arrangement with\nCanada, the Treasury will buy the\nbulk of the Dominion\u2019s newly\nmined silver production. This un\nderstanding has been continued\nonly through January.\nThe understanding with China,\nby which this Government ex\nchanges gold for Chinese silver,\nhas been extended for a six-month\nperiod ending June 30, Morgen\nthau said.\nFor more than a year, the Treas\nury has been buying practically\nthe entire newly mined silver out\nput of both Canada and Mexico.\nLarge silver purchases also have\nbeen made from Peru, although\nno understanding has ever been\nreached with the South American\nrepublic.\nEarlier this week, the United\nStates agreed to buy Mexican sil\nver through January.\nHitch-Hike Slayer\nInsane, Is Finding\nELYRIA, Ohio, Dec. 30 (1.N.5.).\nAlexander Mane ff, 21-year-old\nhitchhiker from West Homestead,\nPa\u201e charged with the attack-mur\nder of Louise Hornbeck at nearby\nGrafton, is \u201cnot now sane,\u201d a\nthree-judge common pleas court\nruled today. Maneff was ordered\ncommitted to the Lima State Hos\npital.\nrespiratory methods the firemen\nattempted to pump life back into\nthe body of Brown. When their\nefforts failed, Dr. O. R. Farrell,\nof Emregency Hospital, pro\nnounced the salesman dead. Coro\nner A. Magruder MacDonald cer\ntified suicide and ordered the body\nturned over to Brown\u2019s widow,\nMrs. Helen C. Brown, a clerk. The\nsalesman left a note ascribing ill\nhealth as the motive for his act.\nTHREE CENTS\nBUSINESS LEVY\nHELD FAILURE,\nREPEAL URGED\n$7,500,000 Is Asked\nAs Lump Sum\nBy PAUL A. CONLIN\nThe District Tax Advisory Com\nmittee recommended to the Com\nmissioners today a 1 per cent sales\ntax, a 1 per cent income tax and\nan increase from $5,000,000 to $7,-\n500,000 in the Federal lump sum\npayment as solution to an esti\nmated deficit of $4,900,000 in Dis\ntrict revenues for the fiscal year\n1939. The taxes would begin July\n1 next.\nThe committee advised aban\ndonment of the business privilege\ntax on gross receipts and based\nits estimates on the assumption\nthe $1.75 per SIOO valuation tax\non real estate will expire June 30,\n1938, restoring the former rate of\n$1.50.\nNO EXEMPTIONS\nIt recommended the sales tax\nbe levied without exemptions. It\nexplained the matter of exemp\ntions is \u201ca question of policy\u201d and\nsaid it felt \u201cthe low rate\u201d with\nthe proposed income tax war\nranted this proviso.\nThe sales tax recommendation\nwas qualified with the clause the\nrate should be increased \u201cnot to\nexceed 2 per centum\u201d if the\nCommissioners believed the esti\nmated $2,500,000 from this source\nshould fall short of its mark.\nIn this connection, the commit\ntee cited the experience garnered\nhere and in other jurisdictions\nwith the collection of the business\nprivilege tax.\nFAVOR EXTENSION\nThe committee also recom\nmended an extension of the rev*\nnue act of 1937 which permits thf\nDistrict to borrow money from\nthe Treasury Department to meet\ngeneral expenses in the event loca.\u2019\nrevenues should fail to reach ex\npec ted proportions.\nIt went on record against th<\nBudget Bureau's transfer of th<\nstreet lighting charge of $765,001\nfrom the general fund to the spe\ncial fund for highways and traffic\nthe committee told the Commis\neration this transfer in estimating\nthe deficit of $4,900,000. If it!\nrecommendations are followed,\nthe cimmittee told the Mommis-\n(Continued on Page 2, Col. 3)\nHeflin Improved,\nDoctor Reports\nLAFAYETTE, Ala., Dec. 30\n(I.N.S.).\u2014J. Thomas Heflin, for\nmer United States Senator, suf\nfering from \u201clobar pneumonia,\u201d\nwas reported by his physicians\nhere today as \u201cmuch improved,\nbut still not out of danger.\u201d Dr.\nN. A. Wheeler said that the\nformer Alabama solon had spent a\n\u201cbetter night\u201d and that the oxygen\ntent had been removed forth\u00ab\npresent.\nINDEX\nPage\nAndrew R. Kelley 8\nBirths and Marriages 18\nBoake Carter 17\nClassified Ads 26,27\nComics 20,21\nDrama 8,9\nEditorials 6\nEvalyn Walsh McLean... 17\nFlora Macdonald 14\nFrank \u201cBuck\u201d O\u2019Neill 23\nHarry Costello 23\nHelen Essary 17\nInquiring Photographer 6\nJackie in Movieland 22\nKirk Miller 23\nPaul Mallon 7\nPeter Carter 14\nRadio 19\nWoman's Page 12","height":"25858","width":"20512"}}
